Widget Development and Deployment Workflow

Here’s a quick rundown on how to develop an html widget using R. I’ll start from the very beginning with how to layout a brand new widget, make changes, test, and then I’ll finish off with a brief mention on how to deploy the widget in Shiny. In terms of helpful resources, I’ve used this RStudio tutorial, the html widgets page, in addition to forking a few github repositories (like this one).

Starting a New Widget

Dependencies

The htmlwidgets package is an R library for creating R bindings to JavaScript libraries. In order to get the framework in place, you’ll need three packages, which you can install (only do this once) with:

install.packages("htmlwidgets")
install.packages("htmltools")
install.packages("devtools")

Scaffolding

Now you’re ready to create a new widget. it’s as simple as:

devtools::create("widgetTitle")            # use the devtools function 'create()' to create a package
setwd("widgetTitle")                       # navigate to your new package directory
htmlwidgets::scaffoldWidget("widgetTitle") # create the scaffolding
devtools::install()                        # installs the package

By default, this will create a widget that takes a single text argument and displays the argument within the HTML element. Test it out with

library(widgetTitle)
widgetTitle("hello, world")

You’ll notice that you now have a few files in your project directory. Luckily, you really only need to pay attention to three of them for now:

  1. The R/widgetTitle.R file is the R function that will invoke your widget. Here’s where you pass arguments from the outside world, like data and params.

  2. The inst/htmlwidgets/widgetTitle.yaml is where we list out the JavaScript and CSS assests we’ll use. Dependencies are included in the inst/htmlwidgets/lib directory. If you really want to get fancy, you can include a bower package with the scaffoldWidget command to download source dependencies that way too.

  3. The inst/htmlwidgets/widgetTitle.js is the JavaScript required to activate the widget. This includes a name and type for the widget and a factory function that takes the object el, width, and height and prepares the HTML element to start receiving values. The return value of the factory function is called a widget instance object. It is a bridge between the htmlwidgets runtime, and the JavaScript visualization that you’re wrapping. As the name implies, each widget instance object is responsible for managing a single widget instance on a page. There are many more details to know about the factory function, but you can find them here.

Widget Workflow: The Rinse and Repeat

You have a framework. You have all the tools. Time to develop. There are a series of four actions that I repeat through while working on widgets:

  1. Make edits to the .R, .js, and .yaml files and save.
  2. Run devtools::install() from the widget root directory
  3. Run library(whatever_your-widget_is_called) to load the widget in your environment
  4. Test out your changes by calling your widget on an example set of data.

One other thing that I found useful was to use the jsonlite library in R, specifically jsonlite::toJSON(), to check how my data frame was being converted to json…which is what happens automatically when you pass data through your widget.

Here’s an example for a widget I have called filterWidget that makes a brushable barchart or histogram, depending on the data.

#---- Step 1 -------#
# make some changes

#---- Step 2 -------#
devtools::install("../filterWidget/")
## Installing filterWidget
## '/Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Resources/bin/R' --no-site-file  \
##   --no-environ --no-save --no-restore --quiet CMD INSTALL  \
##   '/Users/reeh135/Documents/Projects/mead/filterWidget'  \
##   --library='/Users/reeh135/Library/R/3.3/library' --install-tests
## 
#---- Step 3 -------#
library(filterWidget)

#---- Step 4 -------#
test_data <- data.frame(Peanut = runif(45), Apple = runif(45)+runif(45), Banana = c(rep("Cat", 25), rep("Bat", 10), rep("Dog",10)))
## Warning in runif(45): '.Random.seed' is not an integer vector but of type
## 'NULL', so ignored
#numerical data
filterWidget("Peanut", test_data)
#categorical
filterWidget("Banana", test_data)

Then, it’s just a matter of making the perfect chart with whatever JavaScript tools you can wield.

Deploying Your Widget in Shiny

This part is surprisingly easy. Your new widget is going to act like a function, with specific Shiny-esque functions attached to it. As with all things Shiny, you’ll do things on the server side and send the output to the ui side. So let’s talk about what happens on the server side first. An example of placing a filterWidget widget instance would go something like this:

library(shiny)
library(filterWidget)
server <- shinyServer(function(input, output) {
  test_data <- data.frame(Peanut = runif(45), Apple = runif(45)+runif(45), Banana = c(rep("Cat", 25), rep("Bat", 10), rep("Dog",10)))
  
  plot_data <- reactive({
    return(test_data[,as.character(input$column)])
  })
  
  output$plot_1 <- renderfilterWidget({
    filterWidget(as.character(input$column), data.frame(plot_data()))
  })
})

Then the ui side uses the second function from the widget, filterWidgetOutput, to render the figure.

ui <- shinyUI(fluidPage(
  selectInput("column", "Column to Plot:",
                choices = colnames(test_data)),
  filterWidgetOutput("plot_1")
))

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

Happy widgeting!
